<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-130-382 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 820 282</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  June 11 1991 n1694* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (UK) 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Infonet uses Cisco routers to link local networks across theworld.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Infonet Services Corp. (Services)Cisco Systems Inc. (Products).andO;Product:   Cisco Systems AGSandplus; FDDI Router (Router device) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Routers (Connector)NetworksTransmission Control Protocol/Internet Protocol (Computer NetworkProtocol).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>INFONET USES CISCO ROUTERS TO LINKandM;LOCAL NETWORKS ACROSS THE WORLDandM;Infonet Corp's new service for interconnecting local area networks on aglobal basis is a native TCP/IP network using Cisco Systems Inc's AGSandplus;routers.andP;  InfoLAN is available at rates from 9.6Kbps to 2.048Mbps, and it isbeing provided on monthly, fixed cost basis.andP;  Infonet will install andmaintain the networks, including user hardware and software.andP;  The Ciscorouters will be resold as part of the service, and each network location willbe connected to a router at the local Infonet facility.andP;  Routers areconnected to Network Equipment Technologies Inc' IDNX switches that make upInfonet's T1 backbone.andP;  Said to provide peer-to-peer communications andsimultaneous support for centralised and distributed applications, it alsoprovides for network uptime and redundancy.andP;  By early 1992, InfoLAN willsupport Novell Inc's Interpacket Exchange, DECnet and AppleTalk protocols, aswell as its own traditional X25 service, and it is evaluating SwitchedMultimegabit Data Service bandwidths for future transmission speedrequirements.andP;  Infonet is now widely held by public telephone operators ledby France Telecom and Deutsche Bundespost Telekom with some half dozenothers, and new service is to be offered in nine countries during June, and afurther five countries will have the service by the first quarter of 1992.andO;</TEXT>